subSubSection.paragraph:
Notes.
– Only two fruits have been retrieved at FI. The largest one [
FI018792
] and the second largest [
FI018793
]. The cross-sectioned (
Fig. 2A
, bottom) and the fourth, slender one (
Fig. 2B
, bottom) are inexplicably missing. Somewhat blurred annotations in Beccari’s handwriting are present on the smooth surface of the husk of each coconut fruit (
Fig. 3
). Probably written by fountain pen or indelible pencil, the two annotations had apparently been overlooked since 1937, when Beccari’s Herbarium Palmarum was acquired by FI (
CUCCUINI & NEPI, 2006
). [
FI018792
] bears “Palyra [sic!] Islands/ (Oceano Pacifico)/ Dal Sig. Rock 1914/ Collez. O. Beccari” (
Fig. 3A
) and – on the opposite side – “Palmyra Islands/ Dal Sig. Rock/ 1914”, the latter also present on [
FI018793
] (
Fig. 3B
). The larger coconut, [
FI018792
], is here chosen as the 
lectotype
of 

Cocos nucifera
f. 
palmyrensis

(
Fig. 4
).
